1160":"1160","about 1131":"about 1131","Llawhaden, Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Llawhaden, Pembrokeshire, Wales","Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales","Llywel, Breconshire, Wales":"Llywel, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llangadog Fawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Gwynfe, Llangadog Fawr, Carmarthenshire, Wales":"Gwynfe, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lewys","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Lewis</i>, <i>Leweis</i>, <i>Lowis</i>, from ancient Germanic (originally West Frankish) <i>Hludwig</i> (itself from <i>hlōd-</i> ‘fame, famous’ + <i>wīg-</i> ‘battle’). This was Latinized as <i>Ludovicus</i> and <i>Chlodovisus</i>, which were gallicized as <i>Clovis</i> or <i>Clouis</i>, French <i>Louis</i>. The name may also appear as <i>Lawis</i>, <i>Laweys</i>, <i>Lawes</i>, by unrounding of the vowel of <i>Lowis</i> on the analogy of the variation between <i>Low</i> and <i>Law</i> as pet forms of Middle English <i>Lourence</i> alias <i>Laurence</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. See   Laws   2 and compare   Lawrence  .","Welsh: adopted for the Welsh personal name <i>Llywelyn</i> (see   Llewellyn  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’. This is one of the most common Old Irish personal names. It is derived from <i>Lugh</i> ‘brightness’, which was the name of a Celtic god."],"variants":[{"name":"Laws","meanings":["English: variant of   Law   (pet form of   Lawrence  ), with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Perhaps a shortened form of Scottish or Irish   McLeish  . Compare   McLaws  ."]},{"name":"Lewison","meanings":["Welsh and English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Lewis   (in Wales this was taken as equivalent to the Welsh personal name   Llewelyn  ). In North America, this surname has reportedly absorbed in some cases the Greek patronymic   Iliopoulos  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic): patronymic from the personal name <i>Lewi</i>, Polish-influenced form of   Levy  ."]},{"name":"McGlew","meanings":["Irish: most probably from <b>Mac Lughaidh</b> ‘son of <i>Lughaidh</i>’, a Gaelic personal name (referencing the god Lugh), sometimes Anglicized as   Lewis  . However, both Woulfe and MacLysaght consider <i>McGlew</i> to be a shortened form of <b>Mac Dhuinnshléibhe</b> (see   McAleavey   and   Dunleavy  )."]},{"name":"Lowis","meanings":["English: variant of   Lewis   1."]}]},{"name":"Elen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now also used outside Wales. It is identical with the Welsh vocabulary word <i>elen</i> ‘nymph’, but this is unlikely to be the origin. It is found in Welsh texts from an early period as an equivalent of <i>Helen</i>, for example as the name of the mother of Constantine, finder of the True Cross."],"variants":[{"name":"Elin","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Elen ."]}]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["1  ‘Sharp blade’.","2  ‘Wind’."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Elen ferch Lewys was born about 1115, in Llangadog in Kidwelly, Carmarthenshire, Wales, United Kingdom as the daughter of Lewys ap Ieuan and Efa ferch Rhys. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Rhydderch Ap Bledri."},"et":{"about 1115–":"umbes 1115–Surnud","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1500–Male":"1500–Surnud","1500–Female":"1500–Surnud","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","–Ma